  saturated fat: 17 g
  carbohydrates: 67 g
  protein: 38 g
---

Pre-heat the oven to 220 degrees. Wash the @Maris Piper Potatoes{2} then chop lengthways into wedges the thickness of your index finger. Toss in @olive oil{1%tbsp} and the @Garlic Salt{1%tsp}, then spread in a single layer on a #baking tray{}. Cook on the top shelf of the oven until crispy (around ~{25%minutes}).

In a #bowl{} mix together the @British Beef Mince{250%g} with @Tomato Ketchup{3/4%tbsp}, a few grinds of @pepper{}, a small pinch of @salt{} and the @Dried Oregano{1}.

Divide the mixture into 2 equal portions and then gently form into burger patties.

> It is important that you press the meat together firmly enough to make it stick yet not so firmly that it becomes densely packed, as this will give a tough texture.

Once the potatoes are almost finished, split the @Brioche Bun{2} in half. Put a #frying pan{} on a hob on medium-high heat. Toast the buns for a couple of minutes on each side then remove.

> You could use your toaster but whatever happens don't let them burn!

Heat @olive oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #non-stick pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, gently add in the patties and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} on each side, turning only once.

> We love dribble-down-your-chin medium/rare which takes around 3 mins on each side but cook them for a little longer if you like.

Whilst you are cooking the second side of the burger lay a slice of @Gouda Cheese{2%slices} on top of each patty for the last minute so that it melts.

Toss @Wild Rocket{2/3%bunch} in a little drizzle of @olive oil{} with a small pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread a little of the remaining @Tomato Ketchup{1/4%tbsp} on the toasted burger buns. Place your burger patty on top then slice the @Vine Tomatoes{1}(sliced thinly widthways). Lay the tomato and rocket on top and serve with your rustic chips on the side.